text: Yep. So the genesis is exactly the point that you made. We started identifying back in the early days that there was a lot more that could be done in terms of indexing or creating exposures that weren't available in the ETF landscape. Part of the segue there too, is I started to appreciate having been inside VanEck, which is first and foremost an ETF shop. That got me access to a lot of other ETF providers and provided a really good look under the hood of just the business of ETFs in general. And it is difficult... If a client, if an institutional or retail client wants a specific tilt on value or a specific take on value, if there's not an ETF that addresses that, then they're out of luck unless they have the ability to do this direct indexing or this indexing as a service. Now, fast forward, technology, again, has really helped disintermediate that. So... And what I mean by that is... So that was the idea for IDX. And it started really as a consulting entity. And then we morphed into more of a full-blown solution focused on this custom indexing as a service where we'll go to clients in exactly the same fashion as you said and say, look, here's... Don't think of an index as an off-the-shelf, take-it-or-leave-it option, which is currently what you have with the ETF landscape. We like to think of it as a menu of options. So if you think about value, there's multiple ways you can define value. You can look at one signal, you can look at multiple signals. You can weight them by value, you can weight them by market cap, you can weight them equally. You can increase the number of definitions of value, both in terms of quantity as well as sophistication. You don't necessarily have to go full tilt, Piotrowski F-score, but you can... There's somewhere in between. And one of the early engagements I had was with actually a company that was looking, it was an insurance company, and they had an asset management arm where they had a very specific definition or they had a very specific definition of value. And they had a very specific exposure they wanted. It was a blend of European dividend value focus. And these were entirely bottoms-up stock pickers. And so they came to me with a 300-megabyte Excel file with 36 different rules or screens for value. And they said, we want you to turn this into an index. And I went back and I was like, guys, it doesn't really work like that. First of all, the value we provide isn't just outsourced quantitative services. It's to help you measure... And justify the complexity, help you build the index. Even if you're coming to us with the recipe, so to speak, we're helping you build it with the highest quality ingredients in the most robust fashion. I want you to be able to cook the same dish with maximum quality all the time under any environment. We must have gone back and forth over months, starting with the simplest version of their rules and then layering, basically creating dozens of indices that would incorporate one more degree of quality or... Sorry, one more degree of... Of complexity. And take it to them and say, there's decreasing returns to complexity, not surprisingly. And to your point about the Laffer curve of complexity, the goal isn't to obviously create the best backtest. It's also not to create the most complex or the simplest product. It's to maximize the sharp ratio of the complexity or of the degrees of freedom. And so that's where, to answer your question directly, that's where I think custom indexing, indexing is a good way to go. And I think that's where I think the best way to go is to is really poised to do well and is in this kind of subset of investor that's big enough, not necessarily huge institutions, but even just bigger, more sophisticated RIAs that have the ability to consume signals directly. They don't necessarily need a 40-act product to invest. They have the sophistication to understand why book to value is different than price earnings. They understand the idea of the trade-off between complexity and complexity. And so I think that's where I think the best way to go is to and degrees of freedom and robustness. And the last point is, again, technology has really made it easy to kind of deliver these custom indices to this group because they themselves, in many cases, kind of have their own trade desks or even they don't need prime brokers anymore like we did in 2010 for the big institutional clients. Even the Charles Schwab's, the IBs, the trading platforms, the custodians have really gotten good at allowing these guys to take in signals, as an example, and incorporate them directly into their model portfolio. And so that's kind of – we had an article a while back where I talked about kind of the technology disintermediating now what I believe to be the ETF landscape. And as this picks up steam, ETFs themselves, they're never going to go away, but they're going to become increasingly obsolete for a certain type of investor who understands that they want something that's not off the shelf and has the ability to take signals and turn it into product. Robert Leonard
